<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Geography">Geography</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pforzheim&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Geography">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Pforzheim is located at the northern rim of the eastern part of the <a href="/wiki/Black_Forest" title="Black Forest">Black Forest</a> (Schwarzwald) and the rim of the hilly country of the <a href="/wiki/Kraichgau" title="Kraichgau">Kraichgau</a>, in an open valley at the confluences of the rivers <a href="/wiki/W%C3%BCrm" title="WÃ¼rm">WÃ¼rm</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nagold" title="Nagold">Nagold</a> and the rivers Nagold and <a href="/wiki/Enz" title="Enz">Enz</a>. Due to its location, this city is also called the "three-valleys town" (<i>Drei-Taeler Stadt</i>) or the "Gateway to the Black Forest" (<i>Pforte zum Schwarzwald / Porta Hercynia</i>). The early settlement (in fact much earlier than the current centers <a href="/wiki/Stuttgart" title="Stuttgart">Stuttgart</a> and <a href="/wiki/Karlsruhe" title="Karlsruhe">Karlsruhe</a>) by the Romans, who constructed a <a href="/wiki/Ford_(river)" title="Ford (river)" class="mw-redirect">ford</a> through the river, shortly past the confluence of the three rivers, for their military highway, is also due to this extraordinary geography. Due to this location, Pforzheim later on became a center for the <a href="/wiki/Timber_rafting" title="Timber rafting">timber-rafting</a> trade which transported timber from the Black Forest via the rivers Wuerm, Nagold, Enz and then the <a href="/wiki/Neckar" title="Neckar">Neckar</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhine" title="Rhine">Rhine</a> to, among other destinations, the Netherlands for use in shipbuilding and the construction of <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam" title="Amsterdam">Amsterdam</a> on poles in a swamp.</p>
<p>Pforzheim and its surrounding area belongs to the "Densely Populated Area Karlsruhe/Pforzheim". Pforzheim has the functions of a regional center (Mittelzentrum) for the towns and municipalities <a href="/wiki/Birkenfeld_(Enz)" title="Birkenfeld (Enz)">Birkenfeld (Enz)</a>, <a href="/wiki/Eisingen" title="Eisingen">Eisingen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Engelsbrand" title="Engelsbrand">Engelsbrand</a>, <a href="/wiki/Friolzheim" title="Friolzheim">Friolzheim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heimsheim" title="Heimsheim">Heimsheim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ispringen" title="Ispringen">Ispringen</a>, <a href="/wiki/K%C3%A4mpfelbach" title="KÃ¤mpfelbach">KÃ¤mpfelbach</a>, <a href="/wiki/Keltern" title="Keltern">Keltern</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kieselbronn" title="Kieselbronn">Kieselbronn</a>, <a href="/wiki/K%C3%B6nigsbach-Stein" title="KÃ¶nigsbach-Stein">KÃ¶nigsbach-Stein</a>, <a href="/wiki/M%C3%B6nsheim" title="MÃ¶nsheim">MÃ¶nsheim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neuenb%C3%BCrg" title="NeuenbÃ¼rg">NeuenbÃ¼rg</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neuhausen_(Enz)" title="Neuhausen (Enz)">Neuhausen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neulingen" title="Neulingen">Neulingen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Niefern-%C3%96schelbronn" title="Niefern-Ãschelbronn">Niefern-Ãschelbronn</a>, <a href="/wiki/%C3%96lbronn-D%C3%BCrrn" title="Ãlbronn-DÃ¼rrn">Ãlbronn-DÃ¼rrn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Remchingen" title="Remchingen">Remchingen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Straubenhardt" title="Straubenhardt">Straubenhardt</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tiefenbronn" title="Tiefenbronn">Tiefenbronn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wiernsheim" title="Wiernsheim">Wiernsheim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wimsheim" title="Wimsheim">Wimsheim</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wurmberg" title="Wurmberg">Wurmberg</a>.<sup class="reference plainlinks nourlexpansion" id="ref_wikipedia"><a class="external autonumber" href="//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pforzheim#endnote_wikipedia">[1]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Neighbouring_communities">Neighbouring communities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pforzheim&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Neighbouring communities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The following towns and communities share borderlines with the City of Pforzheim. Below they are mentioned in clockwise order, beginning to the north of the city. Except for Unterreichenbach, which belongs to the district of <a href="/wiki/Calw" title="Calw">Calw</a>, all of them are included in the <a href="/wiki/Enz_(district)" title="Enz (district)" class="mw-redirect">Enz</a> district.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Ispringen" title="Ispringen">Ispringen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neulingen" title="Neulingen">Neulingen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kieselbronn" title="Kieselbronn">Kieselbronn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Niefern-%C3%96schelbronn" title="Niefern-Ãschelbronn">Niefern-Ãschelbronn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wurmberg" title="Wurmberg">Wurmberg</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wimsheim" title="Wimsheim">Wimsheim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Friolzheim" title="Friolzheim">Friolzheim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tiefenbronn" title="Tiefenbronn">Tiefenbronn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neuhausen_(Enz)" title="Neuhausen (Enz)">Neuhausen (Enz)</a>, <a href="/wiki/Unterreichenbach" title="Unterreichenbach">Unterreichenbach</a>, <a href="/wiki/Engelsbrand" title="Engelsbrand">Engelsbrand</a>, <a href="/wiki/Birkenfeld_(Enz)" title="Birkenfeld (Enz)">Birkenfeld (Enz)</a>, <a href="/wiki/Keltern_(Baden)" title="Keltern (Baden)" class="mw-redirect">Keltern</a> and <a href="/wiki/K%C3%A4mpfelbach" title="KÃ¤mpfelbach">KÃ¤mpfelbach</a><sup class="reference plainlinks nourlexpansion" id="ref_wikipedia"><a class="external autonumber" href="//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pforzheim#endnote_wikipedia">[2]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="City_wards">City wards</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pforzheim&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: City wards">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The city of Pforzheim consists of <b>16 city wards</b>. The communities BÃ¼chenbronn, Eutingen on Enz, Hohenwart, Huchenfeld and WÃ¼rm, which by way of the latest regional administrative reform during the 1970s were incorporated into Pforzheim's <a href="/wiki/Local_government" title="Local government">administration</a>, are represented by independent <a href="/wiki/Local_government" title="Local government">community councils</a> and community administrations according to Â§ 8 and following paragraphs of the main city-ordinance of Pforzheim. In important matters concerning any of these communities the opinions of the respective community councils must be taken into consideration. However, final decisions on the matter will be made by the Pforzheim city council.</p>
<ul>
<li>City center (<i>Innenstadt</i>)</li>
<li>Northern ward (<i>Nordstadt</i>)</li>
<li>Eastern ward (<i>Oststadt</i>)</li>
<li>Southeastern ward (<i>SÃ¼doststadt</i>)</li>
<li>Southwestern ward (<i>SÃ¼dweststadt</i>)</li>
<li>Western ward (<i>Weststadt</i>)</li>
<li>Arlinger</li>
<li>BrÃ¶tzingen</li>
<li>Buckenberg and Hagenschiess; including Altgefaell, Haidach and Wald-Siedlung</li>
<li>BÃ¼chenbronn including Sonnenberg</li>
<li>Sonnenhof</li>
<li>DillweiÃenstein</li>
<li>Eutingen on Enz including MÃ¤uerach</li>
